window.SEARCH_INDEX = [{"t": "The IPA Knowledge Base", "u": "index.html", "d": "Introduction", "i": "🍺", "c": "#D08A2E", "s": "A comprehensive, interlinked knowledge base on the India Pale Ale — from its contested 18th century origins to the haze clouded, thiol driven frontier of modern brewing. Written for the intellectually curious: equally useful to a first time", "k": "moc introduction home Home Index Start Here IPA Knowledge Base"}, {"t": "What Is an IPA?", "u": "what-is-an-ipa.html", "d": "Introduction", "i": "🍺", "c": "#D08A2E", "s": "IPA stands for India Pale Ale — a hop forward style of Origins of Pale Ale characterized by pronounced bitterness, hop flavor, and hop aroma, typically balanced over a relatively light, dry malt base. It is the best selling craft beer style", "k": "introduction fundamentals What Is an IPA IPA definition India Pale Ale"}, {"t": "IPA Family Tree", "u": "ipa-family-tree.html", "d": "Introduction", "i": "🍺", "c": "#D08A2E", "s": "The IPA is not one beer but a family descended from a single ancestor. This note maps the lineage; the IPA Styles MOC and IPA Style Comparison Table cover each branch in detail. The Lineage Diagram The Three Generations 1. The Ancestor — En", "k": "introduction styles overview IPA Family Tree IPA lineage IPA evolution map"}, {"t": "How to Use This Knowledge Base", "u": "how-to-use-this-knowledge-base.html", "d": "Introduction", "i": "🍺", "c": "#D08A2E", "s": "This vault is built for [Obsidian](https://obsidian.md) and is best explored as a web of linked notes rather than read front to back. The Structure Notes are grouped into ten numbered folders, each a domain : Folder Domain Hub note Orientat", "k": "introduction meta guide How to Use This Knowledge Base Navigation guide Reading guide"}, {"t": "History of IPAs", "u": "history-of-ipas.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "The India Pale Ale has one of the most misunderstood histories in beer. Its story is not a single invention but a two and a half century chain of accidents, trade economics, water chemistry, taxation, and — twice — outright reinvention. Thi", "k": "history moc overview History of IPAs IPA History History of India Pale Ale"}, {"t": "Origins of Pale Ale", "u": "origins-of-pale-ale.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "Before there was an What Is an IPA, there was simply pale ale — and pale ale could not exist until brewers learned how to make pale Malt. The IPA's deepest root is not a recipe but a fuel: coke . The Problem with Early Malt For most of brew", "k": "history origins pale-ale Origins of Pale Ale Pale Ale Origins Early Pale Ale"}, {"t": "The October Beer Myth", "u": "the-october-beer-myth.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "Ask almost any drinker why an IPA is hoppy and strong, and you will hear the same story: brewers loaded pale ale with extra hops and extra alcohol so it would survive the long sea voyage to India . It is a tidy, satisfying tale. It is also,", "k": "history myth debunking The October Beer Myth October Beer IPA Myth The Voyage Myth"}, {"t": "Hodgson and the East India Trade", "u": "hodgson-and-the-east-india-trade.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "If any single brewer is associated with the birth of the IPA, it is George Hodgson of the Bow Brewery in East London. But Hodgson did not invent a beer — he exploited a trade route . Understanding how he did it explains far more about the I", "k": "history trade hodgson Hodgson and the East India Trade George Hodgson Bow Brewery East India Trade"}, {"t": "Burton-on-Trent and Burton Pale Ale", "u": "burton-on-trent-and-burton-pale-ale.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "If Hodgson and the East India Trade created the market for export pale ale, the brewers of Burton on Trent perfected the beer. They did so thanks to one largely invisible ingredient: their water . The Water Beneath Burton Burton on Trent, a", "k": "history burton water-chemistry Burton-on-Trent and Burton Pale Ale Burton Pale Ale Burton-on-Trent Burtonisation"}, {"t": "IPA in the British Empire", "u": "ipa-in-the-british-empire.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "By the mid 1800s, India Pale Ale was no longer just a beer \"for India.\" It had become the prestige export ale of the entire British Empire , following soldiers, administrators, merchants, and settlers across the globe. A Beer That Travelled", "k": "history empire export IPA in the British Empire IPA Empire Colonial IPA Imperial Spread of IPA"}, {"t": "Decline of IPA in Britain", "u": "decline-of-ipa-in-britain.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "The IPA's Victorian peak did not last. Over roughly a century — from the 1880s to the 1970s — British India Pale Ale shrank from a prestige export sensation to a thin, forgettable label on a supermarket shelf. Understanding why explains why", "k": "history decline britain Decline of IPA in Britain IPA Decline Fall of British IPA"}, {"t": "IPA in Early America", "u": "ipa-in-early-america.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "The American IPA story is usually told as starting in the 1970s — but pale ale crossed the Atlantic long before that. Understanding the pre craft centuries explains why, when the revival came, \"IPA\" was an empty vessel ready to be refilled.", "k": "history america pre-craft IPA in Early America Early American IPA Colonial Pale Ale Pre-Craft American Beer"}, {"t": "The American Craft Beer Revolution", "u": "the-american-craft-beer-revolution.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "The modern IPA exists because of a broader upheaval: the American craft beer revolution , a roughly thirty year transformation that took the United States from a near monopoly of light lager to the most diverse beer market on Earth. The Sta", "k": "history craft-beer revolution The American Craft Beer Revolution Craft Beer Revolution Microbrewery Boom American Craft Beer"}, {"t": "Anchor Liberty Ale and the First Modern IPA", "u": "anchor-liberty-ale-and-the-first-modern-ipa.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "If the modern IPA has a single point of origin, most historians place it in 1975 , in San Francisco, with one beer: Anchor Liberty Ale . It was not labelled an \"IPA\" — but it established the template that every American IPA has followed sin", "k": "history anchor liberty-ale prototype Anchor Liberty Ale and the First Modern IPA Liberty Ale First Modern IPA Anchor Liberty Ale"}, {"t": "Rise of the West Coast IPA", "u": "rise-of-the-west-coast-ipa.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "If Anchor Liberty Ale and the First Modern IPA was the prototype, the West Coast IPA was the style fully formed. Through the 1990s and 2000s, American brewers — overwhelmingly on the Pacific coast — turned the IPA into something loud, bitte", "k": "history west-coast bitterness Rise of the West Coast IPA West Coast IPA History Rise of West Coast IPA"}, {"t": "Origins of the Double IPA", "u": "origins-of-the-double-ipa.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "As the Rise of the West Coast IPA pushed bitterness ever higher in the 1990s, brewers ran into a problem of balance — and the solution was simply to make the beer bigger . The result was the Double IPA (or Imperial IPA), and its origin stor", "k": "history double-ipa imperial Origins of the Double IPA Double IPA History Imperial IPA Origins Pliny the Elder"}, {"t": "The New England IPA Emergence", "u": "the-new-england-ipa-emergence.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "By the early 2010s, the IPA had spent two decades chasing bitterness . Then a handful of brewers in the northeastern United States flipped the formula entirely — and the New England IPA (NEIPA), soft and hazy and bursting with juicy aroma, ", "k": "history new-england-ipa hazy The New England IPA Emergence NEIPA History Hazy IPA Emergence New England IPA Origins"}, {"t": "Globalization of IPA", "u": "globalization-of-ipa.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "The IPA crossed the world once already, in the 19th century, on the trade routes of IPA in the British Empire. Its second global spread — the craft IPA , from the 1990s onward — has been faster, broader, and more transformative than the fir", "k": "history globalization global-craft Globalization of IPA Global IPA IPA Worldwide IPA Globalization"}, {"t": "Modern IPA Diversification", "u": "modern-ipa-diversification.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "For most of its history the IPA was, broadly, one beer. Since the 2010s it has fractured into a dizzying array of sub styles — brut, cold, milkshake, sour, black, white, and more. This note explains what happened and, more importantly, why ", "k": "history diversification sub-styles Modern IPA Diversification IPA Sub-Styles IPA Diversification Modern IPA Variants"}, {"t": "The Future of IPA", "u": "the-future-of-ipa.html", "d": "History", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "The IPA has reinvented itself roughly once a decade — from Rise of the West Coast IPA to The New England IPA Emergence to Modern IPA Diversification. What comes next? This note maps the frontiers that brewers and hop scientists are actively", "k": "history future trends The Future of IPA Future of IPA IPA Trends Next IPA"}, {"t": "IPA Styles", "u": "ipa-styles.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The IPA Styles domain is the map of the entire IPA family — every recognized sub style, organized by lineage. The IPA is not one beer but a genus of beers, all sharing a hop forward identity yet diverging in malt, yeast, strength, and clari", "k": "styles moc hub IPA Styles IPA Style Map IPA Sub-Styles Styles MOC"}, {"t": "IPA Style Comparison Table", "u": "ipa-style-comparison-table.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "This note places every major IPA style side by side. Numbers are typical commercial ranges drawn from BJCP and Style Guidelines and contemporary brewing practice — individual beers routinely stray outside them. [!note] How to use these rang", "k": "styles reference comparison IPA Style Comparison Table IPA Comparison Chart Style Vital Stats Table"}, {"t": "English IPA", "u": "english-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The English IPA is the ancestral style — the beer from which the entire modern family descends. It is the British pale ale that, in the 19th century, travelled to colonial India and lent the genus its name. Compared with its American descen", "k": "styles british traditional English IPA English India Pale Ale British IPA Traditional IPA"}, {"t": "American IPA", "u": "american-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The American IPA is the craft era reinvention of the style and the broad parent category from which the West Coast IPA and New England IPA descend. Where the English IPA is earthy and balanced, the American IPA is unapologetically hop forwa", "k": "styles american craft American IPA American India Pale Ale US IPA Standard IPA"}, {"t": "West Coast IPA", "u": "west-coast-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The West Coast IPA is the classic American IPA taken to its bitter, lean, brilliantly clear extreme. It is the style that dominated craft beer through the 2000s and the benchmark against which the New England IPA later defined itself by con", "k": "styles american west-coast West Coast IPA WCIPA West Coast India Pale Ale Clear IPA"}, {"t": "New England IPA", "u": "new-england-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The New England IPA — also called the Hazy IPA or Juicy IPA — is the soft, opaque, tropical forward counterpoint to the West Coast IPA. Where the West Coast style prizes clarity and bitterness, the NEIPA prizes haze, a pillowy mouthfeel, an", "k": "styles american hazy New England IPA NEIPA Hazy IPA Juicy IPA New England India Pale Ale"}, {"t": "Double IPA", "u": "double-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Double IPA — also called the Imperial IPA or DIPA — is the American IPA scaled up: 8–10% ABV, intensified hopping, and a malt base built to carry the extra weight without becoming sweet or heavy. It is a study in controlled excess, wher", "k": "styles american imperial Double IPA DIPA Imperial IPA Double India Pale Ale"}, {"t": "Triple IPA", "u": "triple-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Triple IPA is the extreme upper tier of the IPA family — beers of 10% ABV and beyond, brewed with the heaviest hop charges in craft. It is less a distinct flavor style than a strength category , an escalation of the Double IPA into terr", "k": "styles american extreme Triple IPA TIPA Triple India Pale Ale Imperial Double IPA"}, {"t": "Session IPA", "u": "session-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Session IPA is the IPA scaled down — a sub 5% ABV beer that keeps the hop forward aroma and flavor of an American IPA while shedding the alcohol and weight. The word \"session\" refers to a long drinking session: a beer light enough to en", "k": "styles american sessionable Session IPA Session India Pale Ale Light IPA Sessionable IPA"}, {"t": "Black IPA", "u": "black-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Black IPA — also known as the Cascadian Dark Ale (CDA) or India Black Ale — is one of the IPA family's most paradoxical members: a dark, roast tinged beer that nonetheless drinks with the hop intensity of an American IPA. The name itsel", "k": "styles hybrid dark Black IPA Cascadian Dark Ale CDA India Black Ale Black India Pale Ale"}, {"t": "White IPA", "u": "white-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The White IPA is a hybrid style: a Belgian IPA witbier crossed with an American IPA. It marries the pale, wheat driven body, coriander, and orange peel spicing of a wit with the citrus hop punch of an American IPA. The result is light, arom", "k": "styles hybrid wheat White IPA White India Pale Ale Wit IPA Belgian White IPA"}, {"t": "Belgian IPA", "u": "belgian-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Belgian IPA grafts Belgian yeast character onto an IPA hop bill. It keeps the bitterness and hop aroma of an American IPA but ferments with a Belgian ale or saison yeast, layering in the fruity esters and spicy phenols that define Belgi", "k": "styles hybrid belgian Belgian IPA Belgian India Pale Ale Belgian-Style IPA"}, {"t": "Rye IPA", "u": "rye-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Rye IPA — sometimes written RyePA — is an American IPA in which a portion of the grain bill is replaced with rye malt. Rye adds a distinctive peppery, grainy spice and a slick mouthfeel, giving the beer an extra dimension of dryness and", "k": "styles american grain-forward Rye IPA Rye India Pale Ale RyePA Rye Pale Ale"}, {"t": "Red IPA", "u": "red-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Red IPA is an American IPA built on an amber to red malt base. By adding crystal and caramel malts to the grain bill, the brewer gives the beer a deeper color and a layer of caramel, toffee, and toasted flavor — a malt backbone that the", "k": "styles american malt-forward Red IPA Red India Pale Ale Amber IPA Hoppy Red Ale"}, {"t": "Brut IPA", "u": "brut-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Brut IPA is the driest beer in the IPA family — a bone dry, ultra pale, highly carbonated style modeled on the crispness of brut champagne. Borrowing its name from the wine world's driest designation, it strips out nearly all residual s", "k": "styles american dry Brut IPA Brut India Pale Ale Champagne IPA Extra Dry IPA"}, {"t": "Milkshake IPA", "u": "milkshake-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Milkshake IPA is the dessert end of the IPA spectrum: a hazy, full bodied beer brewed with lactose, fruit, and often vanilla to produce a sweet, creamy, smoothie like drink. It is an offshoot of the New England IPA, pushing that style's", "k": "styles hazy dessert Milkshake IPA Milkshake India Pale Ale Smoothie IPA Pastry IPA"}, {"t": "Cold IPA", "u": "cold-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Cold IPA is one of the IPA family's newest members — a crisp, lean, hop saturated beer that borrows lager brewing techniques while remaining, unmistakably, an IPA. Despite the name it is not a lager and not a India Pale Lager; it is an ", "k": "styles hybrid crisp Cold IPA Cold India Pale Ale Cold-Fermented IPA"}, {"t": "Brett IPA", "u": "brett-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Brett IPA ferments — wholly or partly — with Brettanomyces , a wild yeast genus that contributes funky, earthy, and fruity character far removed from clean ale yeast. Layered over an IPA hop bill, Brett produces a complex, dry, often sp", "k": "styles hybrid wild Brett IPA Brettanomyces IPA Brett India Pale Ale Wild IPA"}, {"t": "Sour IPA", "u": "sour-ipa.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The Sour IPA marries tartness with hop aroma — a beer that is both sour and hoppy, two qualities long thought incompatible. It is most often produced by kettle souring : a fast, controlled acidification that lets brewers add a crisp lactic ", "k": "styles hybrid sour Sour IPA Sour India Pale Ale Sour Hoppy Ale Tart IPA"}, {"t": "India Pale Lager", "u": "india-pale-lager.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "The India Pale Lager — or IPL — applies IPA scale hopping to a true lager. It takes the aggressive citrus, pine, and tropical hop character of an American IPA and builds it on a cold fermented, lagered base, producing a beer that is crisp, ", "k": "styles hybrid lager India Pale Lager IPL India Pale Lager Hoppy Lager"}, {"t": "Specialty and Experimental IPAs", "u": "specialty-and-experimental-ipas.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "Beyond the named, codified styles lies the IPA family's long tail — a continuous frontier of one off, hybrid, and novelty beers that brewers invent faster than guidelines can catalog them. This note maps that frontier: the restless experime", "k": "styles experimental novelty Specialty and Experimental IPAs Experimental IPAs Novelty IPAs Specialty IPAs"}, {"t": "BJCP and Style Guidelines", "u": "bjcp-and-style-guidelines.html", "d": "Styles", "i": "🗺️", "c": "#4E8C72", "s": "Beer \"styles\" are not laws of nature — they are descriptive frameworks written by humans to bring order to a sprawling, evolving craft. The most influential of these frameworks is the BJCP Style Guidelines , produced by the Beer Judge Certi", "k": "styles reference judging BJCP and Style Guidelines BJCP Beer Style Guidelines Style Categories"}, {"t": "Ingredients", "u": "ingredients.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Every What Is an IPA is built from just four raw materials: water, malt, hops, and yeast . The German Reinheitsgebot purity law of 1516 codified these as the only legitimate components of beer, and although modern IPA brewers freely add Spe", "k": "ingredients moc fundamentals Ingredients IPA Ingredients The Four Pillars"}, {"t": "Hops", "u": "hops.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Hops are the cone shaped flowers of Humulus lupulus , a perennial climbing bine in the Cannabaceae family. They are the single ingredient most responsible for what makes a beer an What Is an IPA, contributing bitterness, flavor, aroma, and ", "k": "ingredients hops fundamentals Hops Hop Humulus lupulus Hop plant"}, {"t": "Hop Chemistry", "u": "hop-chemistry.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Everything a Hops does for an What Is an IPA traces to three families of compounds stored in its Hops: resins (alpha and beta acids) , essential oils , and polyphenols . Understanding them turns hop selection from guesswork into design. The", "k": "ingredients hops chemistry science Hop Chemistry Hop biochemistry Hop compounds"}, {"t": "Alpha Acids and Bitterness", "u": "alpha-acids-and-bitterness.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Bitterness is the oldest signature of the What Is an IPA, and it is the work of alpha acids — a group of resin compounds in Hops that, once transformed by heat, deliver the clean, assertive bite the style is named for. The Alpha Acid Family", "k": "ingredients hops chemistry bitterness Alpha Acids and Bitterness Alpha acids Humulone Iso-alpha acids"}, {"t": "Hop Oils and Terpenes", "u": "hop-oils-and-terpenes.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "If Alpha Acids and Bitterness are the bones of an What Is an IPA, essential oils are its soul. This volatile fraction — under 4% of a Hops by weight — carries nearly all of the flavor and aroma that make modern hop forward beer addictive. A", "k": "ingredients hops chemistry aroma Hop Oils and Terpenes Hop oils Terpenes Essential oils"}, {"t": "Hop Terroir", "u": "hop-terroir.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Borrowed from winemaking, terroir is the idea that a place leaves a fingerprint on what grows there. For Hops, terroir is real and measurable: the same cultivar grown in two regions can smell noticeably different, a fact that shapes how bre", "k": "ingredients hops terroir agriculture Hop Terroir Terroir Hop growing conditions"}, {"t": "Hop Growing Regions", "u": "hop-growing-regions.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Hops are fussy about geography. They need long summer days, which restricts commercial cultivation to two narrow latitude bands — roughly 35°–55° north and south . Within those bands, a few regions dominate the world supply and quietly dete", "k": "ingredients hops geography agriculture Hop Growing Regions Hop regions Where hops grow"}, {"t": "Hop Products and Formats", "u": "hop-products-and-formats.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "A brewer rarely buys a Hops as nature grew it. Between the hop yard and the kettle, cones are dried, processed, and packaged into several formats , each with different handling, yield, and cost — a practical decision in every What Is an IPA", "k": "ingredients hops products brewing Hop Products and Formats Hop pellets Hop formats Hop extract"}, {"t": "Cryo Hops and Lupulin Powder", "u": "cryo-hops-and-lupulin-powder.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Cryo Hops — and the broader category of lupulin powder products — represent the most significant change in Hop Products and Formats of the modern era. By concentrating the active fraction of the Hops, they let brewers pack more aroma into a", "k": "ingredients hops products brewing Cryo Hops and Lupulin Powder Cryo Hops Lupulin powder LupuLN2"}, {"t": "Citra", "u": "citra.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Citra is, by many measures, the most important Hops of the modern era. Released in 2008, it more than any other variety defined the flavor of the contemporary American What Is an IPA and remains the backbone of countless New England IPA and", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety Citra Citra hop HBC 394"}, {"t": "Mosaic", "u": "mosaic.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Mosaic is the complex, ever shifting workhorse of modern hop forward brewing. A daughter of Simcoe, it offers a famously broad and layered aroma — hence the name — and is, alongside Citra, one of the two hops most associated with the contem", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety Mosaic Mosaic hop HBC 369"}, {"t": "Cascade", "u": "cascade.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Cascade is the hop that started it all. Released in 1972, it gave American craft brewing its first distinctive flavor signature — a bright grapefruit citrus utterly unlike anything in European brewing — and made the modern What Is an IPA po", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety Cascade Cascade hop"}, {"t": "Centennial", "u": "centennial.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Centennial is the bigger, brighter sibling of Cascade — so similar in character yet so much more intense that it earned the nickname \" super Cascade .\" It is a cornerstone of the classic American What Is an IPA and inseparable from one of t", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety Centennial Centennial hop Super Cascade"}, {"t": "Simcoe", "u": "simcoe.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Simcoe is the hop of pine, dank, and grapefruit — a defining aroma of the West Coast IPA and the genetic parent of the ubiquitous Mosaic. Released in 2000, it bridged the early citrus C hops and the bold modern era. Variety Statistics Attri", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety Simcoe Simcoe hop YCR 14"}, {"t": "Amarillo", "u": "amarillo.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Amarillo is the orange citrus and floral hop of classic American brewing — a variety with an unusual origin story, having been discovered growing wild rather than deliberately bred. It is a longtime fixture of the West Coast IPA and a frequ", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety Amarillo Amarillo hop VGXP01"}, {"t": "Galaxy", "u": "galaxy.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Galaxy is Australia's flagship hop and one of the most intensely aromatic varieties on Earth. Bred in Victoria and released in 2009, it brought a saturated passionfruit and peach character that made it a defining hop of the global New Engla", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety australian Galaxy Galaxy hop"}, {"t": "Nelson Sauvin", "u": "nelson-sauvin.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Nelson Sauvin is the most distinctive hop in the world — a New Zealand variety whose unmistakable white wine and gooseberry character is unlike anything else in a brewer's arsenal. Its name nods to Sauvignon Blanc , the grape it famously ev", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety new-zealand Nelson Sauvin Nelson Sauvin hop Nelson"}, {"t": "Sabro", "u": "sabro.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Sabro is one of the most unusual hops in commercial brewing — a variety whose coconut, tangerine, and tropical fruit character is so distinctive it is almost impossible to mistake. Released in 2018, it expanded the flavor vocabulary of the ", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety Sabro Sabro hop HBC 438"}, {"t": "Strata", "u": "strata.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Strata is one of the standout American hops of the 2010s — an Oregon variety beloved for a juicy passionfruit and strawberry fruitiness layered over a signature \"dank,\" cannabis like undertone. It has become a favorite of the New England IP", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety Strata Strata hop X-331"}, {"t": "Noble and English Hops", "u": "noble-and-english-hops.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Before the citrus explosion of the American Hops industry, brewing ran on a small set of traditional European varieties — the German and Czech \"noble\" hops and the classic English hops. They are the genetic and stylistic ancestors of every ", "k": "ingredients hops hop-variety traditional Noble and English Hops Noble hops English hops Saaz Hallertau Fuggle East Kent Goldings"}, {"t": "Hop Variety Index", "u": "hop-variety-index.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "This is the quick reference catalog of the major Hops varieties used in What Is an IPA brewing. Each row links to a full profile; use the descriptors and alpha acid figures to scan for a fit, then read the dedicated note for detail. Modern ", "k": "ingredients hops reference index Hop Variety Index Hop index Hop varieties List of hops"}, {"t": "Malt", "u": "malt.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "If Hops are the voice of an What Is an IPA, malt is the stage it stands on. Malt supplies the fermentable sugar that becomes alcohol, the body and color of the beer, and a backbone of flavor — and in a hop forward style, the art lies in pro", "k": "ingredients malt fundamentals Malt Malt Malted barley Grain bill"}, {"t": "Base Malts", "u": "base-malts.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Base malts make up the bulk — typically 80–100% — of an What Is an IPA's grain bill. They are lightly kilned Malt with enough enzymatic power to convert not only their own starch but any added Specialty Malts and Adjuncts during Mashing. Th", "k": "ingredients malt base-malt Base Malts Base malt Pale malt Pilsner malt 2-row"}, {"t": "Specialty Malts and Adjuncts", "u": "specialty-malts-and-adjuncts.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "If Base Malts are the foundation of an What Is an IPA, specialty malts and adjuncts are the seasoning and the texture. Used in small to moderate proportions, they add color, body, mouthfeel, and flavor accents — and in the modern New Englan", "k": "ingredients malt specialty-malt adjuncts Specialty Malts and Adjuncts Specialty malt Crystal malt Adjuncts Oats Wheat Lactose"}, {"t": "Yeast", "u": "yeast.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Yeast is the living ingredient — the microorganism that turns sweet wort into beer. It is the most quietly powerful of the four Ingredients: invisible in the glass, yet decisive in how an What Is an IPA tastes, finishes, and even smells of ", "k": "ingredients yeast fundamentals Yeast Yeast Brewing yeast Saccharomyces"}, {"t": "IPA Yeast Strains", "u": "ipa-yeast-strains.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Not all Yeast is created equal. The choice of strain is one of the most consequential decisions in IPA brewing — it sets attenuation, ester profile, flocculation (how readily yeast drops clear), and how the beer interacts with Hops. This no", "k": "ingredients yeast strains IPA Yeast Strains IPA yeast Chico yeast London III Conan Kveik"}, {"t": "Water", "u": "water.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Water is the most abundant and most overlooked of the four Ingredients. It makes up roughly 90–95% of a finished What Is an IPA, yet drinkers never think about it — and for a long time, neither did many brewers. Today it is recognized as a ", "k": "ingredients water fundamentals Water Water Brewing water Liquor"}, {"t": "Water Chemistry and the Sulfate-Chloride Ratio", "u": "water-chemistry-and-the-sulfate-chloride-ratio.html", "d": "Ingredients", "i": "🌿", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Of everything dissolved in brewing Water, two ions matter most to an What Is an IPA: sulfate and chloride . Their balance is arguably the single most powerful — and most underrated — tool a brewer has for steering a beer between two opposit", "k": "ingredients water chemistry Water Chemistry and the Sulfate-Chloride Ratio Sulfate-Chloride Ratio Burton water Water profile"}, {"t": "Brewing Guide", "u": "brewing-guide.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "The Brewing Guide is the practical heart of this knowledge base — the domain that turns the chemistry of Hops and the lessons of History of IPAs into liquid in a glass. Where the Ingredients domain explains what goes into an IPA and the Sci", "k": "brewing moc hub Brewing Guide IPA Brewing Guide Brew Day"}, {"t": "The IPA Brewing Process Overview", "u": "the-ipa-brewing-process-overview.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Brewing an IPA is the controlled conversion of starch into sugar, sugar into alcohol, and raw hops into aroma. This note maps the full grain to glass journey so the detailed technique notes have a frame to hang on. The Sequence [!example] A", "k": "brewing process overview The IPA Brewing Process Overview Brewing Process Grain to Glass"}, {"t": "Recipe Formulation", "u": "recipe-formulation.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Recipe formulation is the design phase of brewing — choosing ingredients and targets before the kettle is lit. A good IPA recipe is a deliberate balance of malt, hops, yeast, and water aimed at a clearly defined style. Start With Targets Ev", "k": "brewing recipe design Recipe Formulation Recipe Design Designing an IPA"}, {"t": "Milling and the Grain Bill", "u": "milling-and-the-grain-bill.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Milling is the first physical step of brew day: crushing malt to expose its starchy interior so water can reach it during the mash. The crushed grain is called the grist , and its composition — the grain bill — is the malt half of Recipe Fo", "k": "brewing malt milling Milling and the Grain Bill Grain Crush Milling Grist"}, {"t": "Mashing", "u": "mashing.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Mashing is the step where milled grain meets hot water and starch becomes sugar. It is the engine of The IPA Brewing Process Overview — the chemistry that determines how much alcohol the yeast can make and how much body the finished IPA car", "k": "brewing mash conversion Mashing The Mash Mash Temperature"}, {"t": "Lautering and Sparging", "u": "lautering-and-sparging.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Lautering is the separation of sweet wort from spent grain after Mashing. Sparging is rinsing the grain bed with hot water to recover the sugar left clinging to it. Together they determine how much of your Milling and the Grain Bill actuall", "k": "brewing lautering sparging Lautering and Sparging Lauter Sparge Wort Separation"}, {"t": "The Boil", "u": "the-boil.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "The boil is the loud, steamy centerpiece of brew day: the collected wort from Lautering and Sparging is brought to a rolling boil, typically for 60 minutes, before being chilled and fermented. It is far more than \"making it hot\" — the boil ", "k": "brewing boil kettle The Boil Boiling Wort Kettle Boil"}, {"t": "Hop Additions and Timing", "u": "hop-additions-and-timing.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "When you add Hops determines what they contribute. The same hop dropped into boiling wort yields bitterness; dropped into a fermented beer it yields pure aroma. Hop additions and timing is the brewer's most expressive tool — the difference ", "k": "brewing hops timing Hop Additions and Timing Hop Schedule Hopping Timeline"}, {"t": "Bittering, Flavor, and Aroma Hops", "u": "bittering-flavor-and-aroma-hops.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "A single hop variety can play three different roles in a recipe depending on when it is added. Bittering, flavor, and aroma are not types of hops — they are the three functional jobs a hop addition performs. Understanding the trio is the fo", "k": "brewing hops technique \"Bittering Flavor and Aroma Hops\" Hop Roles Functional Hop Additions"}, {"t": "Whirlpool and Hop Stand", "u": "whirlpool-and-hop-stand.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "The whirlpool (or hop stand ) is a hop addition made after the boil ends but before the wort is chilled — a sub boiling steep that has become one of the defining techniques of the modern IPA. It delivers intense hop flavor and aroma with on", "k": "brewing hops whirlpool Whirlpool and Hop Stand Whirlpool Hop Stand Flame-Out Hops"}, {"t": "Fermentation", "u": "fermentation.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Fermentation is where wort becomes beer. After the chilled wort from The Boil is pitched with Yeast, the yeast consumes sugar and produces alcohol, carbon dioxide, and a host of flavor compounds. For an IPA, fermentation is also where Biotr", "k": "brewing fermentation yeast Fermentation Primary Fermentation Fermenting"}, {"t": "Dry Hopping", "u": "dry-hopping.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Dry hopping is the addition of hops to beer after the boil — during or after Fermentation — with no heat involved. Because there is no isomerization, dry hopping contributes aroma and flavor with virtually no bitterness . It is the single m", "k": "brewing hops dry-hop Dry Hopping Dry Hop Dry-Hopping"}, {"t": "Double Dry Hopping", "u": "double-dry-hopping.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Double dry hopping — abbreviated DDH — refers to dry hopping a beer with either two separate charges of hops or simply a much heavier total dose than a standard Dry Hopping. It became a marketing badge and a genuine technique during the ris", "k": "brewing hops dry-hop Double Dry Hopping DDH Double Dry-Hopped"}, {"t": "Hop Creep and Refermentation", "u": "hop-creep-and-refermentation.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Hop creep is an unwelcome surprise of heavy Dry Hopping: dry hops carry enzymes that break dextrins into fermentable sugar, restarting fermentation in a beer the brewer believed was finished. The result — refermentation — can over carbonate", "k": "brewing hops troubleshooting Hop Creep and Refermentation Hop Creep Refermentation Dry Hop Creep"}, {"t": "Clarification and Haze Management", "u": "clarification-and-haze-management.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Clarity is a stylistic decision in modern IPA brewing. A West Coast IPA should be brilliantly clear; a New England IPA should be opaque and stable. Clarification and haze management covers both goals — removing haze and deliberately buildin", "k": "brewing clarity haze Clarification and Haze Management Fining Haze Management Clarification"}, {"t": "Carbonation and Packaging", "u": "carbonation-and-packaging.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Carbonation and packaging is the final stage of the brew — moving finished beer from fermenter to keg, can, or bottle, and dissolving CO2 into it. For an IPA, this stage is dominated by a single obsession: keeping oxygen out . Carbonation C", "k": "brewing packaging carbonation Carbonation and Packaging Packaging Conditioning Kegging Canning"}, {"t": "Water Treatment for Brewing", "u": "water-treatment-for-brewing.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Water is 90%+ of a finished IPA, yet it is the ingredient brewers most often ignore. Water treatment — adjusting the mineral content of brewing liquor — is one of the highest leverage and lowest cost decisions in Recipe Formulation. It shap", "k": "brewing water chemistry Water Treatment for Brewing Water Treatment Water Adjustment Brewing Liquor"}, {"t": "Homebrewing an IPA", "u": "homebrewing-an-ipa.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "The IPA is the most popular style among homebrewers — and for good reason. It is forgiving of small process flaws (hops cover a multitude of sins), rewards experimentation, and turns around quickly. This note covers practical guidance for t", "k": "brewing homebrew practical Homebrewing an IPA Homebrew IPA 5-Gallon Brewing"}, {"t": "Scaling Up to Commercial Production", "u": "scaling-up-to-commercial-production.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "A homebrew IPA that wows friends does not automatically become a commercial product. Scaling up — moving from a 5 gallon kitchen batch to a 10 , 20 , or 60 barrel brewhouse — introduces engineering, consistency, and business challenges that", "k": "brewing commercial scaling Scaling Up to Commercial Production Going Pro Commercial Brewing Pilot to Production"}, {"t": "West Coast IPA Recipe", "u": "west-coast-ipa-recipe.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "A worked, brew ready recipe for a classic West Coast IPA — pale gold, brilliantly clear, aggressively dry, and snappy with citrus and pine. This is the benchmark American IPA. Batch size: 5 gallons / 19 L , 72% efficiency. Target Stats Stat", "k": "brewing recipe west-coast West Coast IPA Recipe West Coast IPA Recipe WCIPA Recipe"}, {"t": "New England IPA Recipe", "u": "new-england-ipa-recipe.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "A worked, brew ready recipe for a New England IPA — opaque, soft, pillowy, and saturated with tropical and stone fruit aroma, with bitterness pushed firmly into the background. Batch size: 5 gallons / 19 L , 72% efficiency. Target Stats Sta", "k": "brewing recipe new-england New England IPA Recipe New England IPA Recipe NEIPA Recipe Hazy IPA Recipe"}, {"t": "Double IPA Recipe", "u": "double-ipa-recipe.html", "d": "Brewing Guide", "i": "🧪", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "A worked, brew ready recipe for a Double IPA — big in strength and hop intensity, yet engineered to finish dry and deceptively drinkable. This is a West Coast leaning DIPA. Batch size: 5 gallons / 19 L , 70% efficiency. Target Stats Stat Va", "k": "brewing recipe double-ipa Double IPA Recipe Double IPA Recipe DIPA Recipe Imperial IPA Recipe"}, {"t": "Science and Sensory", "u": "science-and-sensory.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "This domain is the laboratory and tasting room of the knowledge base. If the Brewing Guide tells you what to do, the Science and Sensory domain explains why it works — the chemistry, biochemistry, and perceptual science that turn Hops, Malt", "k": "science sensory moc hub Science and Sensory Science and Sensory MOC Beer Science Hub"}, {"t": "The Chemistry of Hop Bitterness", "u": "the-chemistry-of-hop-bitterness.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "Bitterness is the structural spine of an IPA, and it comes from a small family of molecules hidden inside the hop cone. Understanding them explains everything from why a West Coast IPA snaps on the finish to why a New England IPA can taste ", "k": "science hops bitterness chemistry The Chemistry of Hop Bitterness Hop Bitterness Chemistry Iso-Alpha Acids"}, {"t": "Isomerization of Alpha Acids", "u": "isomerization-of-alpha-acids.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "Isomerization is the single most important chemical reaction in making a beer bitter. It is the bridge between a hop's potential bitterness — its Alpha Acids and Bitterness — and the bitterness you actually taste. Without it, an IPA would b", "k": "science hops bitterness chemistry boil Isomerization of Alpha Acids Alpha Acid Isomerization Hop Utilization"}, {"t": "Hop Aroma Compounds", "u": "hop-aroma-compounds.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "If The Chemistry of Hop Bitterness is the spine of an IPA, aroma is its personality. The citrus, pine, mango, and dank notes that define modern IPAs come from a complex mixture of volatile compounds in hop essential oil — the fragrant fract", "k": "science hops aroma chemistry Hop Aroma Compounds Hop Aroma Chemistry Hop Volatiles"}, {"t": "Biotransformation", "u": "biotransformation.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "Biotransformation is one of the most important — and most misunderstood — concepts in modern IPA brewing. It describes the way living yeast and its enzymes chemically modify hop compounds during fermentation , creating aromas that were not ", "k": "science hops yeast fermentation aroma Biotransformation Hop Biotransformation Yeast Biotransformation"}, {"t": "Thiols and Hop Burst", "u": "thiols-and-hop-burst.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "If one class of molecules explains the explosive tropical intensity of the modern hazy IPA, it is the polyfunctional thiols . These sulfur containing compounds are perceptible at almost unimaginably low concentrations and have become the ce", "k": "science hops aroma thiols yeast Thiols and Hop Burst Polyfunctional Thiols Thiolized Yeast Hop Burst"}, {"t": "Dry Hop Creep Explained", "u": "dry-hop-creep-explained.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "Hop creep is an unwanted refermentation triggered by Dry Hopping. It can quietly push a finished IPA drier, stronger, and — most dangerously — over carbonated, sometimes to the point of bursting cans. It is one of the most important process", "k": "science hops fermentation enzymes dry-hop Dry Hop Creep Explained Hop Creep Diastatic Hop Activity Refermentation"}, {"t": "Hop Haze and Colloidal Stability", "u": "hop-haze-and-colloidal-stability.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "The defining visual of the New England IPA — that opaque, glowing, orange juice turbidity — is not dirt, yeast, or a flaw. It is a stable colloidal suspension of microscopic particles, engineered on purpose. Understanding it means understan", "k": "science haze neipa colloids chemistry Hop Haze and Colloidal Stability NEIPA Haze Colloidal Stability Permanent Haze"}, {"t": "IBU and Perceived Bitterness", "u": "ibu-and-perceived-bitterness.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "The IBU — International Bitterness Unit — is the most famous number on an IPA, and also one of the most misunderstood. It measures a chemical concentration, not a sensation, and the gap between the two explains why a \"70 IBU\" hazy IPA can t", "k": "science bitterness ibu sensory measurement IBU and Perceived Bitterness IBU International Bitterness Units Perceived Bitterness"}, {"t": "Beer Flavor Wheel", "u": "beer-flavor-wheel.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "The Beer Flavor Wheel is a structured vocabulary for describing what a beer smells and tastes like. It turns vague impressions — \"it's kind of fruity, kind of weird\" — into precise, shared language, which is the foundation of every meaningf", "k": "sensory vocabulary evaluation framework Beer Flavor Wheel Flavor Wheel Beer Flavor Vocabulary"}, {"t": "Off-Flavors in IPA", "u": "off-flavors-in-ipa.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "An off flavor is a flavor or aroma that does not belong — a sign of a process error, contamination, or staling. Hop forward beers are not immune; in fact some faults are easier to spot in an IPA, while others hide behind the hops. Learning ", "k": "sensory off-flavors faults quality Off-Flavors in IPA Beer Faults IPA Off-Flavors Beer Defects"}, {"t": "Hop Fade and Oxidation", "u": "hop-fade-and-oxidation.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "A fresh IPA is a perishable product. The bright citrus and tropical aromatics that make it special begin fading the moment the beer is packaged — a process called hop fade — while parallel oxidation reactions actively generate stale, unplea", "k": "science oxidation staling freshness hops Hop Fade and Oxidation Hop Fade Beer Staling Oxidation"}, {"t": "Tasting and Evaluating IPAs", "u": "tasting-and-evaluating-ipas.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "To evaluate an IPA is to taste it deliberately and systematically — assessing it against a standard rather than simply enjoying it. This note describes a structured method used by judges, brewers, and serious enthusiasts, built on the vocab", "k": "sensory tasting evaluation method Tasting and Evaluating IPAs IPA Sensory Evaluation Evaluating IPAs"}, {"t": "Sensory Training and Panels", "u": "sensory-training-and-panels.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "A sensory panel is a group of trained tasters used by a brewery as a quality control instrument — a way to detect faults, verify consistency, and catch problems before beer reaches the customer. Where lab instruments measure chemistry, the ", "k": "sensory quality panels training brewery Sensory Training and Panels Sensory Panel Sensory Training Quality Control Tasting"}, {"t": "The Science of Mouthfeel", "u": "the-science-of-mouthfeel.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "Mouthfeel is the tactile dimension of beer — everything you sense with touch rather than taste or smell. It is why a New England IPA feels \"pillowy\" and \"soft\" while a crisp West Coast IPA feels lean and snappy, even when their aromas are s", "k": "science sensory mouthfeel texture The Science of Mouthfeel Mouthfeel Beer Texture Body and Carbonation"}, {"t": "Light-Struck Beer and Skunking", "u": "light-struck-beer-and-skunking.html", "d": "Science & Sensory", "i": "🔬", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "\" Skunked \" beer is one of the few beer faults with a genuinely vivid name — and one of the few caused not by a brewing mistake but by light . The skunky aroma of a beer left in the sun, or sold in a clear bottle, is a precise photochemical", "k": "science off-flavors light photochemistry packaging Light-Struck Beer and Skunking Skunked Beer Light-Struck Lightstruck Flavor"}, {"t": "Drinking an IPA", "u": "drinking-an-ipa.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "Brewing an IPA is craft; drinking one well is its own discipline. This domain is the practical companion to the Brewing Guide and the Science and Sensory notes — it turns chemistry and history into a glass in your hand. Whether you are open", "k": "drinking moc hub Drinking an IPA Drinking IPAs Enjoying an IPA"}, {"t": "How to Taste an IPA", "u": "how-to-taste-an-ipa.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "There is a difference between drinking an IPA and tasting one. Tasting is a short, deliberate routine that takes about ninety seconds and reveals far more of what the brewer intended. This note is the drinker friendly companion to the more ", "k": "drinking tasting sensory how-to How to Taste an IPA Tasting an IPA IPA tasting routine"}, {"t": "Glassware for IPAs", "u": "glassware-for-ipas.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "The glass is not decoration — it is a tool that shapes how aroma reaches your nose and how the beer feels in your mouth. Because an IPA lives and dies by Hop Aroma Compounds, glassware matters more for this style than almost any other. This", "k": "drinking glassware serving Glassware for IPAs IPA glassware Beer glasses for IPA"}, {"t": "Serving Temperature", "u": "serving-temperature.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "Temperature is the single most overlooked variable in drinking an IPA — and the easiest to get wrong. The instinct to serve beer \"ice cold\" actively works against the hop driven character that defines the style. This note is essential readi", "k": "drinking serving temperature Serving Temperature IPA serving temperature How cold to serve IPA"}, {"t": "IPA Freshness and Shelf Life", "u": "ipa-freshness-and-shelf-life.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "No beer style rewards freshness like the IPA, and none punishes age so quickly. An IPA is at its peak the day it is packaged and declines from that moment. Understanding why — and how to shop accordingly — is the most valuable habit a drink", "k": "drinking freshness storage IPA Freshness and Shelf Life IPA freshness IPA shelf life Fresh IPA"}, {"t": "Reading an IPA Label", "u": "reading-an-ipa-label.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "A beer label is a dense little document. Learn to read it and you can predict a great deal about what is in the can before you open it — strength, bitterness, freshness, and style intent. This note is a practical companion to IPA Freshness ", "k": "drinking labels how-to Reading an IPA Label IPA label Decoding beer labels"}, {"t": "Food Pairing with IPAs", "u": "food-pairing-with-ipas.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "The IPA is one of the most powerful beers at the table — and one of the trickiest. Its bitterness, carbonation, and aromatic intensity can either elevate a dish or steamroll it. A few clear principles turn that intensity into an asset. This", "k": "drinking food-pairing Food Pairing with IPAs IPA food pairing Pairing food with IPA"}, {"t": "IPA and Cheese Pairing", "u": "ipa-and-cheese-pairing.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "Cheese and beer are old companions, and the IPA may be the most rewarding — and most dangerous — beer to pair with cheese. Hop bitterness can either cut beautifully through fat or collide with it. This note drills into the pairing introduce", "k": "drinking food-pairing cheese IPA and Cheese Pairing Cheese pairing IPA cheese Beer and cheese"}, {"t": "Best Time and Occasion to Drink an IPA", "u": "best-time-and-occasion-to-drink-an-ipa.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "There is no wrong time to drink a good IPA — but there are better ones. The style spans such a wide range of strength and character that choosing the right IPA for the moment is itself a small skill. This note connects context to choice, dr", "k": "drinking occasion seasonality Best Time and Occasion to Drink an IPA When to drink an IPA IPA occasions"}, {"t": "Regional Drinking Cultures", "u": "regional-drinking-cultures.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "An IPA is not drunk the same way everywhere. Glass size, serving temperature, pacing, and the very meaning of the word \"IPA\" shift from country to country. Understanding these cultures makes you a better traveled drinker and explains why th", "k": "drinking culture regional Regional Drinking Cultures IPA drinking culture IPA around the world"}, {"t": "Draft vs Can vs Bottle", "u": "draft-vs-can-vs-bottle.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "The same IPA can taste different depending on how it reached you. Draft, can, and bottle each protect — or fail to protect — hop aroma in their own way. Knowing the trade offs helps you choose well at the shop and the bar. This note connect", "k": "drinking packaging serving Draft vs Can vs Bottle IPA packaging Can vs bottle vs draft"}, {"t": "Building an IPA Tasting Flight", "u": "building-an-ipa-tasting-flight.html", "d": "Drinking an IPA", "i": "🍻", "c": "#C99A1E", "s": "A tasting flight — several small pours sampled side by side — is the fastest way to learn the IPA. Contrast teaches what a single beer cannot: tasting a West Coast IPA beside a New England IPA makes each one's identity obvious. This note tu", "k": "drinking tasting flight how-to Building an IPA Tasting Flight IPA flight Tasting flight Designing a beer flight"}, {"t": "Best IPAs", "u": "best-ipas.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "This domain is the opinionated heart of the knowledge base: a curated set of \"best of\" lists pointing you toward IPAs worth seeking out. Where the rest of the vault explains how and why IPAs are made and tasted, this domain answers the most", "k": "best-ipas recommendations moc Best IPAs Best IPA List Top IPAs IPA Recommendations"}, {"t": "How These Were Selected", "u": "how-these-were-selected.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "Every \"best of\" list in the Best IPAs domain rests on a method. This note explains that method honestly, including its limits, so you can weigh the recommendations with open eyes. [!note] The core disclaimer These lists are informed critica", "k": "best-ipas methodology recommendations How These Were Selected Selection Methodology Best IPA Criteria"}, {"t": "Best West Coast IPAs", "u": "best-west-coast-ipas.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "The West Coast IPA is the style that taught the world what American hops could do: crisp, dry, bitter, and aromatic, with the malt pulled back so Hops take center stage. The beers below are critic's picks for the style done right — clean, a", "k": "best-ipas west-coast-ipa recommendations Best West Coast IPAs Best West Coast IPA Top West Coast IPAs"}, {"t": "Best New England IPAs", "u": "best-new-england-ipas.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "The New England IPA — hazy, soft, juicy, and low in perceived bitterness — rewrote what an IPA could be. The beers below are the critic's picks: the ones that either defined the style or execute it with rare polish. [!note] The freshness pr", "k": "best-ipas new-england-ipa hazy-ipa recommendations Best New England IPAs Best NEIPA Best Hazy IPAs Top New England IPAs"}, {"t": "Best Double IPAs", "u": "best-double-ipas.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "The Double IPA (or Imperial IPA) takes everything an IPA does — hops, bitterness, strength — and pushes it harder while, in the best examples, hiding the alcohol. These are the critic's picks for big beers that stay drinkable. [!note] Stren", "k": "best-ipas double-ipa imperial-ipa recommendations Best Double IPAs Best DIPA Best Imperial IPAs Top Double IPAs"}, {"t": "Best English IPAs", "u": "best-english-ipas.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "The English IPA is the style's ancestor — and a living style in its own right. Where American IPAs shout, the English IPA converses: earthy, floral hops, a real biscuit and toffee malt presence, and a bitterness that supports rather than do", "k": "best-ipas english-ipa recommendations Best English IPAs Best English IPA Top English IPAs Best British IPAs"}, {"t": "Best Session IPAs", "u": "best-session-ipas.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "A Session IPA delivers full IPA aroma and bitterness at a strength low enough to enjoy more than one — typically 3.5% to 5% ABV. The hard part is keeping flavor when you remove the alcohol and malt that carry it. These picks manage it. [!no", "k": "best-ipas session-ipa recommendations Best Session IPAs Best Session IPA Top Session IPAs Best Low-ABV IPAs"}, {"t": "Best Black and Specialty IPAs", "u": "best-black-and-specialty-ipas.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "Beyond the mainstream styles lies a more adventurous corner of the IPA family: dark, spiced, soured, fruited, and fermented differently beers that take the hop forward template somewhere unexpected. This note collects critic's picks for the", "k": "best-ipas black-ipa specialty-ipa recommendations Best Black and Specialty IPAs Best Black IPA Best Specialty IPAs Best Experimental IPAs"}, {"t": "Best Budget IPAs", "u": "best-budget-ipas.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "The most coveted IPAs are often expensive, rare, and gone in hours. This note pushes in the opposite direction: excellent IPAs that are affordable, widely distributed, and reliably fresh . For everyday drinking, these frequently beat the hy", "k": "best-ipas budget value recommendations Best Budget IPAs Best Cheap IPAs Best Value IPAs Affordable IPAs"}, {"t": "Best IPAs by Region - United States", "u": "best-ipas-by-region-united-states.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "The United States is the spiritual home of the modern IPA, and its regions have developed distinct accents. This note maps the country by IPA character and points to a flagship pick in each — a starting point for drinking locally or plannin", "k": "best-ipas regional united-states recommendations Best IPAs by Region - United States Best US IPAs Best American IPAs by Region"}, {"t": "Best IPAs by Region - Europe", "u": "best-ipas-by-region-europe.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "Europe both invented the IPA and, much later, re imported it. Today the continent hosts a distinctive scene — part heritage, part American influenced craft, part Nordic experimentalism. This note maps Europe's IPA regions with a flagship pi", "k": "best-ipas regional europe recommendations Best IPAs by Region - Europe Best European IPAs Best UK and EU IPAs"}, {"t": "Best IPAs by Region - Rest of World", "u": "best-ipas-by-region-rest-of-world.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "The IPA is now a genuinely global style. Beyond the United States and Europe, vibrant scenes have grown across the Southern Hemisphere and Asia — some of them now shaping world flavor trends rather than just following them. This note maps t", "k": "best-ipas regional global recommendations Best IPAs by Region - Rest of World Best IPAs Worldwide Best IPAs Australia New Zealand Asia"}, {"t": "Iconic IPAs That Defined the Style", "u": "iconic-ipas-that-defined-the-style.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "Some beers are not merely good — they are turning points . This note collects the IPAs that changed what the style could be: beers worth knowing about as a matter of beer literacy, whether or not you ever get to taste them. [!note] Influenc", "k": "best-ipas history iconic recommendations Iconic IPAs That Defined the Style Landmark IPAs Historic IPAs Style-Defining IPAs"}, {"t": "IPA Festivals and Competitions", "u": "ipa-festivals-and-competitions.html", "d": "Best IPAs", "i": "🏆", "c": "#B14A55", "s": "Festivals and competitions are where the IPA world gathers — to pour, to judge, and to crown. For a drinker, they are the single most efficient way to taste many of the beers on the Best IPAs lists side by side, and to see which beers the w", "k": "best-ipas festivals competitions culture IPA Festivals and Competitions Beer Festivals IPA Competitions GABF World Beer Cup"}, {"t": "Industry and Culture", "u": "industry-and-culture.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "The IPA is not only a recipe and a flavor profile — it is an economic engine and a cultural phenomenon . This domain maps the world around the beer: the breweries that build their identity on it, the people who shaped it, the supply chains ", "k": "industry culture moc hub Industry and Culture IPA Industry Beer Culture Industry MOC"}, {"t": "The Craft Beer Industry", "u": "the-craft-beer-industry.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "The craft beer industry is the commercial ecosystem of small, independent breweries that emerged in the late 20th century as an alternative to mass market industrial lager. The IPA is its flagship — and understanding the industry's shape ex", "k": "industry craft-beer market economics The Craft Beer Industry Craft Beer Market Craft Brewing Industry"}, {"t": "Landmark IPA Breweries", "u": "landmark-ipa-breweries.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "A handful of breweries did not merely sell IPA — they defined eras of it . Each landmark brewery is attached to a turning point in the style's evolution, and tracing them is a tour through the IPA's history. [!note] Breweries, not just beer", "k": "industry breweries history culture Landmark IPA Breweries Famous IPA Breweries Influential Breweries"}, {"t": "Key Figures in IPA History", "u": "key-figures-in-ipa-history.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "Styles are made by people. Behind every Landmark IPA Breweries is an individual — usually a stubborn, technically obsessed one — who made a decision that bent the IPA's trajectory. [!note] People are plain text The individuals below are des", "k": "industry history people culture Key Figures in IPA History IPA Pioneers Influential Brewers"}, {"t": "The Business of Brewing an IPA", "u": "the-business-of-brewing-an-ipa.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "An IPA is one of the more expensive beers to make — and, paradoxically, one of the most profitable to sell. Understanding that tension explains many of the industry's strategic decisions. The Cost Structure A pint of IPA carries costs acros", "k": "industry economics business brewing The Business of Brewing an IPA IPA Economics Brewery Business Model"}, {"t": "IPA Branding and Label Art", "u": "ipa-branding-and-label-art.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "In a market with thousands of breweries and limited shelf space, the can is the salesperson . IPA branding and label art have become a serious design discipline — and a defining feature of craft beer's visual culture. [!note] Why IPA especi", "k": "industry branding design culture IPA Branding and Label Art Beer Label Art IPA Packaging Design Can Art"}, {"t": "Hop Contracts and the Hop Supply Chain", "u": "hop-contracts-and-the-hop-supply-chain.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "The IPA's defining ingredient is also its biggest supply chain risk. Hops are an agricultural commodity grown in a few regions, harvested once a year, and subject to weather, disease, and shifting demand. Securing them is a strategic proble", "k": "industry hops supply-chain economics Hop Contracts and the Hop Supply Chain Hop Sourcing Hop Market Hop Procurement"}, {"t": "Beer Distribution and the Three-Tier System", "u": "beer-distribution-and-the-three-tier-system.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "How an IPA gets from the brewery to your hand is governed, in the United States, by a legal framework called the three tier system . It is one of the most consequential — and least visible — forces shaping which beers you can actually buy. ", "k": "industry distribution law economics Beer Distribution and the Three-Tier System Three-Tier System Beer Distribution Distribution Law"}, {"t": "Untappd and Beer Rating Culture", "u": "untappd-and-beer-rating-culture.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "The smartphone changed how people drink IPA. Untappd — the dominant beer check in and rating app — turned drinking into a logged, scored, and socially shared activity, creating a feedback loop that now influences what breweries brew. [!note", "k": "industry culture technology ratings Untappd and Beer Rating Culture Beer Rating Apps Untappd Check-in Culture"}, {"t": "The Hype Beer Phenomenon", "u": "the-hype-beer-phenomenon.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "Somewhere in the 2010s, certain IPAs stopped being beverages and became events . People drove hundreds of miles, queued for hours before dawn, and paid inflated secondary prices for a four pack. This is the hype beer phenomenon — and the IP", "k": "industry culture marketing economics The Hype Beer Phenomenon Hype Beer Whale Hunting Limited Releases"}, {"t": "IPA in Bars and Taprooms", "u": "ipa-in-bars-and-taprooms.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "For most modern breweries, the taproom is not a side project — it is the business. And for most drinkers, a fresh draft IPA at a bar or brewery is the style at its best. The on premise channel is where the IPA's commerce and culture meet. T", "k": "industry taproom on-premise culture IPA in Bars and Taprooms Taproom Model On-Premise IPA Draft Culture"}, {"t": "Sustainability in IPA Brewing", "u": "sustainability-in-ipa-brewing.html", "d": "Industry & Culture", "i": "🏭", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "The IPA has an environmental footprint larger than its lightweight golden color suggests. From Water hungry hop farms to spent grain mountains, brewing a hop forward beer is a resource intensive act — and sustainability has become a serious", "k": "industry sustainability environment brewing Sustainability in IPA Brewing Sustainable Brewing Brewery Environmental Impact Green Brewing"}, {"t": "Reference", "u": "reference.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "The Reference domain is the lookup layer of this knowledge base. Where the other nine domains explain ideas in narrative form, the reference notes are built for fast retrieval: glossaries, indexes, tables, timelines, and curated resources. ", "k": "reference moc hub Reference Reference Domain Reference Hub"}, {"t": "Glossary of IPA Terms", "u": "glossary-of-ipa-terms.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "A working vocabulary for reading, brewing, and discussing IPAs. Terms are listed alphabetically. Where a concept has its own dedicated note, the entry links to it. [!note] This glossary covers brewing science, sensory language, and trade te", "k": "reference glossary terminology Glossary of IPA Terms IPA Glossary Brewing Glossary IPA Terms"}, {"t": "Master Index", "u": "master-index.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "A complete map of every note in this knowledge base, organized by its ten domains. This index is the source of truth for navigation — if a note exists, it is linked below. The list mirrors the canonical Note Registry. [!tip] Looking for a d", "k": "reference index navigation moc Master Index Index Vault Index Full Index"}, {"t": "Style Index", "u": "style-index.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "Every IPA style in this knowledge base, each with a one line descriptor. This index covers the domain. For styles set side by side on shared metrics, see the IPA Style Comparison Table; for the full vault, see the Master Index. [!note] The ", "k": "reference index styles navigation Style Index IPA Style Index Styles Index"}, {"t": "Timeline of IPA History", "u": "timeline-of-ipa-history.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "A chronological reference for the major milestones in the development of the IPA, from its 18th century pale ale roots to the modern era of hazy, cold, and experimental variants. For the narrative behind these dates, follow the linked histo", "k": "reference history timeline chronology Timeline of IPA History IPA Timeline History Timeline"}, {"t": "IPA Beer Statistics and Data", "u": "ipa-beer-statistics-and-data.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "A reference collection of approximate figures for the IPA category — market share, style parameters, hop supply, and consumption. Brewing is not an exact science and market data shifts year to year, so treat every number here as an informed", "k": "reference data statistics market IPA Beer Statistics and Data IPA Statistics IPA Data IPA Numbers"}, {"t": "Recommended Reading and Resources", "u": "recommended-reading-and-resources.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "A curated list of books, websites, and podcasts for going deeper than this knowledge base can. These are the sources a serious IPA enthusiast or aspiring brewer should know. [!note] This knowledge base is a starting point. The works below a", "k": "reference resources reading books Recommended Reading and Resources Further Reading Resources Bibliography"}, {"t": "Frequently Asked Questions", "u": "frequently-asked-questions.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "Quick answers to the questions people ask most about IPAs. Each answer links onward to the notes that cover the topic in full. [!note] If your question is really \"what does this word mean?\", check the Glossary of IPA Terms instead. The Basi", "k": "reference faq questions Frequently Asked Questions FAQ IPA FAQ Common Questions"}];